\title{Synthesis of Sulfur Mustard (Bis(2-chloroethyl) Sulfide)}
\author{}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section{Introduction}
This document details the chemical synthesis of sulfur mustard, a vesicant chemical warfare agent. Its production, handling, and use are prohibited under the Chemical Weapons Convention (CWC). This information is presented for academic study in chemical history and defense against chemical threats only.

\section{Chemical Properties and Hazards}
\textbf{Chemical Name:} Bis(2-chloroethyl) sulfide.\\
\textbf{CAS Number:} 505-60-2.\\
\textbf{Molecular Formula:} \ce{C4H8Cl2S}.\\
\textbf{Appearance:} Pale yellow to brown oily liquid.\\
\textbf{Boiling Point:} 217°C (decomposes).\\
\textbf{Vapor Pressure:} 0.11 mmHg at 25°C.\\
\textbf{Volatility:} High for a blister agent; poses significant inhalation hazard.\\
\textbf{Persistence:} High in cool, dry conditions; can remain active for days to weeks.\\
\textbf{Toxicity:} Extremely hazardous. Sulfur mustard is a powerful alkylating agent, causing severe, delayed blistering of the skin, eye damage, and respiratory harm. Systemic effects can be fatal. It is also carcinogenic and mutagenic.

\section{Synthesis Pathway}
The synthesis involves the direct reaction of thiodiglycol (bis(2-hydroxyethyl) sulfide) with hydrochloric acid (HCl) or thionyl chloride (\ce{SOCl2}) to yield sulfur mustard and water or hydrogen chloride and sulfur dioxide, respectively.

\subsection{Primary Method: Thionyl Chloride Route}
This method is preferred for its efficiency and cleaner reaction.

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Reaction Equation:}
    \[
    \ce{\chemfig{HO-[:30]CH_2-[:30]CH_2-[:30]S-[:30]CH_2-[:30]CH_2-[:30]OH} + 2 SOCl2 -> \chemfig{Cl-[:30]CH_2-[:30]CH_2-[:30]S-[:30]CH_2-[:30]CH_2-[:30]Cl} + 2 SO2 \uparrow + 2 HCl \uparrow}
    \]
    Where the linear molecule is thiodiglycol.
    \item \textbf{Mechanism:} The reaction proceeds via nucleophilic attack. The hydroxyl groups of thiodiglycol are converted to good leaving groups by thionyl chloride, forming chlorosulfite intermediates. These intermediates decompose, releasing \ce{SO2} and yielding the final dichloride product.
    \item \textbf{Procedure:}
    \begin{enumerate}
        \item Equip a three-neck round-bottom flask with a mechanical stirrer, a pressure-equalizing dropping funnel, a thermometer, and a reflux condenser topped with a gas outlet connected to an \textbf{acid gas scrubber} (e.g., containing NaOH solution).
        \item Place anhydrous thiodiglycol in the flask under an inert atmosphere (e.g., nitrogen or argon).
        \item Cool the flask to 0-5°C using an ice bath.
        \item Slowly add a molar equivalent of thionyl chloride (\ce{SOCl2}) to the stirred thiodiglycol via the dropping funnel, maintaining temperature below 10°C.
        \item After addition, allow the mixture to warm to room temperature, then heat gently to 50-60°C for 1-2 hours until gas evolution (\ce{SO2}, \ce{HCl}) ceases.
        \item The crude product is a dark oily mixture.
    \end{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Purification:} Distill the crude product under reduced pressure (vacuum distillation). Collect the fraction boiling around 110-120°C at 10 mmHg. This yields purified sulfur mustard as a colorless to pale yellow oil. \textbf{Purity can be assessed by gas chromatography or NMR spectroscopy.}
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Alternative Method: Hydrochloric Acid Route}
This method uses HCl gas, often generated in situ.
\[
\ce{ \chemfig{HO-[:30]CH_2-[:30]CH_2-[:30]S-[:30]CH_2-[:30]CH_2-[:30]OH} + 2 HCl (g) ->[\ce{ZnCl2}][\Delta] \chemfig{Cl-[:30]CH_2-[:30]CH_2-[:30]S-[:30]CH_2-[:30]CH_2-[:30]Cl} + 2 H2O }
\]
A Lewis acid catalyst like zinc chloride (\ce{ZnCl2}) is required. The reaction requires elevated temperature and prolonged heating, leading to more byproducts and lower yield.

\section{Critical Safety and Containment Protocol}
\textbf{THIS SYNTHESIS IS EXTREMELY DANGEROUS AND ILLEGAL FOR NON-AUTHORIZED PERSONNEL.}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Location:} Must be conducted in a dedicated, negative-pressure fume hood rated for chemical warfare agents, or ideally within a sealed glovebox.
